{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Indians in Iran |poptime = |popplace = [[Tehran]], [[Zahidan]], [[Abdan]] |langs = [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Hindi]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] |rels = [[Hinduism]]{{·}}[[Zoroastrianism]]{{·}}[[Sikhism]]{{·}}[[Islam]] |related-c = [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Non-resident Indian and Person of Indian Origin]], [[Desi]] }}
Between the late 19th and early 20th centuries, many wealthy [[Parsis]], began to travel to Iran from Bombay and Gujarat, to revive the Zoroastrian faith and traditions among the stagnating Zoroastrian community in Iran at the time, with prominent personalities such as civil rights activist, [[Manekji Limji Hateria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zoroastrian.org.uk/vohuman/Library/Maneckji%20Limji%20Hatari%20in%20Iran.htm |title=Maneckji Limji Hatari in Iran |publisher=Zoroastrian.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-05-31}}</ref> of [[Surat]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritageinstitute.com/zoroastrianism/parsi/surat3.htm|title=Parsi-Zoroastrian Settlement. Surat. Page 3|first=Ed|last=Eduljee|website=www.heritageinstitute.com}}</ref> gaining local renown.
In 1920s, about 180 Indian families went to [[Zahidan]]. Following this initial influx, some of them started settling down in the nearby towns of [[Birijand]], [[Zabol]] and [[Mashhad]]. In 1950s, more Indians migrated to Iran and settled primarily in [[Tehran]]. They consisted of [[Sikh]]s and [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]]s. In the 1960s and early 1970s, about 10,000 Indian doctors, engineers, and teachers moved to Iran as a response to the open policies initiated by the [[Mohammed Reza Pahlavi|Shah of Iran]], but most of them left Iran after the [[Iranian revolution]].
Now, there are few hundred people each concentrated in and around Tehran and Zahidan, primarily engaged in various small businesses. A majority are still Indian citizens. They continue to maintain strong links with India, especially in matters of children's education, marriage and property acquisition.
